flowRoot.flowPara: Wind the bobbin

Put desired thread spoon on spool holder and follow diagram on machine to run thread towards bobbin winder. Bobbin is initially threaded up through hole on top. Pop bobbin on winder holder and push right. Hold on to the thread initially and start winding by pressing foot pedal, then continue winding until about 3/4 full. push bobbin to left to pop it out.
Upper threading

Turn knob towards you to reveal thread take-up lever. following diagram on machine, run thread around, down, back up and over take-up lever, back down, through the metal slit, through eye of needle, down under presser foot and towards back left of machine.
Lower threading
Bobbin is loaded into the machine with thread oriented counterclockwise. follow diagram on machine to run thread down, up and around to the left of bobbin.
Use needle to pull lower thread up

Hold the upper thread with your fingers. Turn the knob towards you once so that needle goes down and pulls the bobbin thread up. You should see a little loop appear. Use scissors or something pointy to pull the bobbin thread up and out from below the presser foot.
Stitch Setting
Set stitch to 01 (center), and set stitch length to 3.5
Type 00 moves needle to left.
For simple projects just stick to a simple stitch type of either 00 and 01.
Backstitch (reverse stitch)

- always begin and end with a backstitch. a backstitch "locks" the ends of a thread to keep the stitch strong and secure. To backstitch, start sewing and quickly press and release the backstitch button (reverse icon) on the machine. You will see the fabric move forward and then reverse direction, essentially stitching over itself. as you near the end of your stitch, make sure to backstitch to lock the end of the stitch. then pull the fabric out and cut the thread using cutter on left side of machine. leave enough thread when you cut to begin next stitch.
Presser foot MUST be DOWN when sewing

Never sew with presser foot up! Presser foot MUST be DOWN to keep fabric from moving around as you sew and to allow the feed dogs to move the fabric through. The presser foot lever is just to the right of needle.
Do not push/pull fabric through machine

Never push or pull fabric through the machine, let the metal feed dogs do the work. Simply guide the fabric as it moves through. You can use the speed control slider to speed up or slow down the machine.
Creasing and folding
Use a ruler & tailor's chalk to draw straight lines, then use a bone folder to create nicely creased folds which you can then fold over & press flat using a hot iron.
Use pins to keep things in place as you work
Use pins to keep fabric in place and aligned as you sew. As needle gets close to a pin, stop sewing, remove pin and then continue sewing.
To make a 90 degree turn (or similar) while sewing
Stop sewing, raise presser foot, adjust fabric position, lower presser foot, resume sewing in new direction.
Terminology

Seam: a line along which two pieces of fabric are sewn together in a garment or other articleHem: the bottom edge of a piece of cloth, folded up and sewn on an item of clothingStraight stitch: Common to all sewing machines, the straight stitch is the basic stitch used for sewing garments, home decor and craft projects. Formed by an interlocking needle and bobbin threads, this versatile stitch can have many faces depending on its use.
